13
00:05:58,100 --> 00:06:01,000
<i>Why did he die?</i>

14
00:06:01,001 --> 00:06:05,000
<i>Sooner or later everyone does.
- Like mommy?</i>

15
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:08,600
<i>Like mommy.</i>

16
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:12,030
<i>Where do they go?</i>

17
00:06:12,031 --> 00:06:14,400
<i>Everyone has their own word.</i>

18
00:06:14,401 --> 00:06:18,800
<i>Heaven, Paradise...</i>

19
00:06:18,801 --> 00:06:21,600
<i>Whatever it's called,
it's someplace beautiful.</i>

20
00:06:21,601 --> 00:06:25,200
<i>How do you know it's beautiful?</i>

21
00:06:25,201 --> 00:06:29,201
<i>Cos that's what I choose to
believe. What do you believe darling?</i>

22
00:07:02,800 --> 00:07:05,700
<i>Good morning, David.</i>

23
00:07:05,900 --> 00:07:09,100
<i>Transmitting message.</i>

24
00:07:10,600 --> 00:07:12,900
<i>No response.</i>

25
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:25,000
Whilst this manner of articulation
is attested indeed in the

26
00:07:25,001 --> 00:07:28,700
Indo-European descendants as
a purely paralinguistic form,

27
00:07:28,701 --> 00:07:34,200
it is phonemic in the ancestral form
dating back five millennium or more.

28
00:07:34,201 --> 00:07:36,700
Now let's attempt Schleicher's Fable.

29
00:07:36,701 --> 00:07:38,900
Repeat after me:

30
00:07:50,500 --> 00:07:52,600
Perfect.

31
00:07:52,601 --> 00:07:56,800
<i>Mr. Lawrence? - Yes?
- Flimsy, sir. - Thank you.</i>

32
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:07,500
<i>You'll do that once too often.
It's only flesh and blood.</i>

33
00:08:07,501 --> 00:08:10,600
<i>Michael George Hartley,
you're a philosopher.</i>

34
00:08:10,601 --> 00:08:13,200
<i>And you're balmy!</i>

35
00:08:16,100 --> 00:08:20,500
<i>Ow! It damn well hurts.
- Certainly, it hurts!</i>

36
00:08:20,501 --> 00:08:22,600
<i>Well, what's the trick then?</i>

37
00:08:22,601 --> 00:08:26,600
<i>The trick, William Potter,
is not minding that it hurts.</i>

38
00:08:26,601 --> 00:08:33,600
The trick, William Potter,
is not minding that it hurts.

39
00:08:59,500 --> 00:09:06,500
<i>Attention! Destination threshold.</i>

40
00:09:06,800 --> 00:09:10,000
<i>Attention! Destination threshold.</i>

41
00:10:11,800 --> 00:10:14,300
Robe.

42
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:26,000
How long?

43
00:10:26,001 --> 00:10:29,700
2 years, 4 months, 18 days,
36 hours, 15 minutes...

44
00:10:29,701 --> 00:10:32,600
Any casualties?
- Casualties, ma'am?

45
00:10:32,601 --> 00:10:37,000
Has anyone died?
- No ma'am, everyone's fine.

46
00:10:38,100 --> 00:10:40,700
Well, then wake them up.

47
00:10:51,300 --> 00:10:54,400
Try to relax Dr. Shaw.

48
00:10:54,401 --> 00:10:57,200
My name is David.

49
00:10:57,201 --> 00:10:59,900
Your mind and body are
in the state of shock,

50
00:10:59,901 --> 00:11:04,400
as a result of stasis.
All that is perfectly normal.

51
00:11:04,401 --> 00:11:08,700
Ellie, we're here baby.

52
00:11:13,900 --> 00:11:18,400
<i>Drink plenty of water,
drink plenty of fluids.</i>

53
00:11:18,401 --> 00:11:21,000
<i>Hydration aids muscle mass.</i>

54
00:11:34,400 --> 00:11:37,400
What the hell is that?

55
00:11:38,600 --> 00:11:43,000
It's Christmas, need a holiday
to show time is still moving.

56
00:11:43,001 --> 00:11:46,000
Mission briefing is about to start captain.

57
00:11:46,001 --> 00:11:48,200
You might want to make your way down.

58
00:11:48,201 --> 00:11:50,600
I haven't had breakfast yet.

59
00:11:50,601 --> 00:11:56,300
Is this seat taken? I'm Millburn,
biology, nice to meet you.

60
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:05,700
No offence, but, I've
been asleep two years.

61
00:12:05,701 --> 00:12:08,600
I isn’t here to be your friend.

62
00:12:08,601 --> 00:12:12,900
I'm here to make money, you got that?

63
00:12:14,700 --> 00:12:16,700
OK.

64
00:12:16,701 --> 00:12:19,800
I bet a hundred credits
it's a terraforming survey.

65
00:12:19,801 --> 00:12:22,700
If it's a survey, they would just tell us.
- This is a corporate run,

66
00:12:22,701 --> 00:12:27,000
they're not telling us shit, come on.
- A hundred, alright, you're on.

67
00:12:31,600 --> 00:12:35,800
You look nervous, Ellie.
- Trying to keep my feet on the ground.

68
00:12:35,801 --> 00:12:38,400
I know you are.
- Good morning.

69
00:12:38,401 --> 00:12:41,800
For those of you I hired personally,

70
00:12:41,801 --> 00:12:44,200
it's nice to see you again.

71
00:12:44,201 --> 00:12:49,000
For the rest of you, I am Meredith Vickers
and it's my job to make sure you do yours.

72
00:12:49,100 --> 00:12:52,800
OK then, on with the show.

73
00:12:57,100 --> 00:13:01,500
<i>Weyland Corporation,
building better worlds.</i>

74
00:13:02,500 --> 00:13:05,300
Hello friends.

75
00:13:06,100 --> 00:13:09,100
My name is Peter Weyland.

76
00:13:09,900 --> 00:13:12,100
I am your employer.

77
00:13:12,101 --> 00:13:16,000
I am recording this 22, June, 2091.

78
00:13:16,001 --> 00:13:20,500
If you're watching it, you
have reached your destination.

79
00:13:20,501 --> 00:13:23,300
And I am long dead.

80
00:13:23,301 --> 00:13:25,900
May I rest in peace.

81
00:13:25,901 --> 00:13:29,700
There's a man sitting with
you today, his name is David.

82
00:13:29,701 --> 00:13:32,800
He is the closest thing
to a son I will ever have.

83
00:13:32,801 --> 00:13:39,100
Unfortunately he is not human, he will
never grow old, and he will never die.

84
00:13:39,500 --> 00:13:43,600
Yet he is unable to appreciate
these remarkable gifts,

85
00:13:43,601 --> 00:13:48,300
for that would require the one
thing that David will never have.

86
00:13:48,301 --> 00:13:50,500
A soul.

87
00:13:50,501 --> 00:13:54,900
I have spent my entire lifetime
contemplating these questions.

88
00:13:54,901 --> 00:13:58,800
Where do we come from?
What is our purpose?

89
00:13:58,801 --> 00:14:00,900
What happens when you die?

90
00:14:00,901 --> 00:14:03,000
And I have finally found two
people who have convinced me

91
00:14:03,001 --> 00:14:05,100
they are on the verge of answering them.

92
00:14:05,400 --> 00:14:09,600
Doctors Holloway and Shaw,
if you would please stand.

93
00:14:10,500 --> 00:14:13,900
As far as you're concerned
they are both in charge.

94
00:14:13,901 --> 00:14:18,600
The Titan, Prometheus, wanted to give
mankind equal footing with the gods,

95
00:14:18,601 --> 00:14:22,700
for that he was cast from Olympus.

96
00:14:23,100 --> 00:14:28,400
Well, my friends, the time has
finally come for his return.

97
00:14:28,401 --> 00:14:31,600
Doctors, please.

98
00:14:33,700 --> 00:14:36,400
Floor is yours.

99
00:14:43,100 --> 00:14:45,700
Ok...

100
00:14:46,900 --> 00:14:49,100
Never had to follow a ghost before.

101
00:14:49,101 --> 00:14:53,000
OK, let me show why you guys are here.

102
00:14:59,800 --> 00:15:05,200
These are images of archaeological
digs, from all over the Earth.

103
00:15:05,201 --> 00:15:09,700
That's Egyptian, Mayan,
Sumerian, Babylonian,

104
00:15:09,701 --> 00:15:12,800
that's Hawaiian there at
the end, and Mesopotamian.

105
00:15:12,801 --> 00:15:15,100
This one here is our
most recent discovery.

106
00:15:15,101 --> 00:15:20,200
It's a 35.000 year old cave painting
from the Isle of Skye in Scotland.

107
00:15:20,201 --> 00:15:24,600
These are ancient civilizations,
that were separated by centuries,

108
00:15:24,601 --> 00:15:29,000
they shared no contact
with one another, and yet...

109
00:15:31,500 --> 00:15:35,100
The same pictogram showing
men worshiping giant beings

110
00:15:35,101 --> 00:15:40,000
pointing to the stars was
discovered at every last one of them.

111
00:15:40,200 --> 00:15:43,700
The only galactic system that matched,

112
00:15:43,701 --> 00:15:47,300
was so far from earth that
there's no way that these primitive

113
00:15:47,301 --> 00:15:50,900
ancient civilizations could
have possibly known about.

114
00:15:50,901 --> 00:15:54,200
But it just so happens,

115
00:15:54,201 --> 00:15:56,900
that that system,

116
00:15:56,901 --> 00:15:59,200
has a sun.

117
00:15:59,201 --> 00:16:01,600
A lot like ours.

118
00:16:01,601 --> 00:16:06,600
And based on our long range
scans, there seems to be a planet.

119
00:16:07,200 --> 00:16:12,200
Just one planet with a moon
capable of sustaining life.

120
00:16:12,600 --> 00:16:16,000
And we arrived there this morning.

121
00:16:16,800 --> 00:16:22,900
So, you say we're here because of a map,
you two kids found in a cave, is that right?

122
00:16:23,100 --> 00:16:26,000
No.
- Yes.

123
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:31,900
No, not a map, an invitation.
- From whom?

124
00:16:32,300 --> 00:16:36,600
We called them engineers.
- Engineers?

125
00:16:36,601 --> 00:16:41,700
Do you mind telling us
what they engineered?

126
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:45,600
They engineered us.

127
00:16:46,500 --> 00:16:49,800
Bullshit.

128
00:16:51,700 --> 00:16:54,500
Do you have anything to back that up?

129
00:16:54,501 --> 00:16:59,900
I mean, look if you're willing to
discount 3 centuries of Darwinism that's...

130
00:17:01,200 --> 00:17:05,500
But how do you know?
- I don't.

131
00:17:05,501 --> 00:17:09,300
But it's what I choose to believe.

132
00:17:35,200 --> 00:17:37,600
Doctors?

133
00:17:37,601 --> 00:17:42,600
Miss Vickers would like to have a
quick word, before the adventure begins.

134
00:17:49,200 --> 00:17:52,100
Nice place.
- It's actually a separate module,

135
00:17:52,101 --> 00:17:55,000
with its own self-contained life support.

136
00:17:55,001 --> 00:18:00,800
Air, food, anything miss Vickers would
need to survive hostile environment.

137
00:18:00,801 --> 00:18:07,400
OK, so she lives on a life boat.
- Yes, I do, I like to minimize risk.

138
00:18:07,401 --> 00:18:11,600
David, why don't you
make the doctors a drink?

139
00:18:11,601 --> 00:18:14,800
I'll take a vodka, up.

140
00:18:14,801 --> 00:18:18,800
Charlie look, it's a Pauling med-pod.

141
00:18:19,200 --> 00:18:22,600
They only made a dozen of these.
- Miss Shaw!

142
00:18:22,601 --> 00:18:25,600
<i>Please verbally state the
nature of your injury.</i>

143
00:18:25,601 --> 00:18:29,900
Please don't touch that. It's a
very expensive piece of machinery.

144
00:18:29,901 --> 00:18:33,700
It does bypass surgeries,
what do you need it for?

145
00:18:34,000 --> 00:18:37,900
I think there might be some
confusion about our relationship.

146
00:18:37,901 --> 00:18:40,500
Weyland found you impressive
enough to fund this mission,

147
00:18:40,501 --> 00:18:43,750
but I'm fairly certain your
"engineers" are nothing but scribbling

148
00:18:43,751 --> 00:18:47,000
of savages living in dirty little caves.

149
00:18:47,001 --> 00:18:51,100
But let's say I'm wrong, and you
do find these beings down there.

150
00:18:51,101 --> 00:18:53,700
You won't engage them.

151
00:18:53,701 --> 00:18:59,000
You won't talk to them, you will
do nothing but report it back to me.

152
00:19:01,400 --> 00:19:06,200
Miss Vickers, is there an agenda
that you're not telling us about?

153
00:19:06,201 --> 00:19:09,700
My company paid a trillion dollars to
find this place and to bring you here.

154
00:19:09,701 --> 00:19:12,800
Had you raised the money
yourself Mr. Holloway,

155
00:19:12,801 --> 00:19:15,900
we'd happily be pursuing your, agenda.

156
00:19:16,700 --> 00:19:18,700
But you didn't.

157
00:19:18,701 --> 00:19:21,800
And that makes you an employee.

158
00:19:22,300 --> 00:19:27,000
If we can't make contact, why
did you even bring us here?

159
00:19:27,001 --> 00:19:30,300
Weyland was a superstitious man.

160
00:19:30,600 --> 00:19:34,300
He wanted a true believer on board.

161
00:19:35,300 --> 00:19:38,000
Cheers.

162
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:43,200
So no response?
- I am sorry, no.

163
00:19:43,201 --> 00:19:46,600
Maybe they didn't understand it.

164
00:19:46,601 --> 00:19:49,900
How are your lessons going, David?

165
00:19:49,901 --> 00:19:55,300
I spent two years deconstructing dozens
of ancient languages, to their roots.

166
00:19:55,301 --> 00:19:57,600
I'm confident I can
communicate with them,

167
00:19:57,601 --> 00:20:01,100
provided your thesis is correct.

168
00:20:01,101 --> 00:20:03,200
Provided it's correct, that's good.

169
00:20:03,201 --> 00:20:07,100
That's why they call
it a thesis, doctor.

170
00:20:09,200 --> 00:20:12,300
What are you smiling about?
- Alright, Mr. Ravel, Mr. Chance,

171
00:20:12,301 --> 00:20:15,300
let's take her down.
- Roger that. - Yes captain.

172
00:20:16,800 --> 00:20:20,300
How are we doing?
- Great.

173
00:20:20,600 --> 00:20:24,600
Alright boss.
- All personnel, this is the captain.

174
00:20:24,601 --> 00:20:27,600
Brace for entry.
- Yes captain.

175
00:20:27,601 --> 00:20:31,000
That means you too Vickers.

176
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:41,000
What is the atmosphere?

177
00:20:41,001 --> 00:20:46,200
Atmosphere is 71% Nitrogen,
21% Oxygen, traces of unknown gas.

178
00:20:46,201 --> 00:20:49,300
Whoa, now that's weather.
- Just like home.

179
00:20:49,301 --> 00:20:51,900
Only if you're breathing
through an exhaust pipe.

180
00:20:51,901 --> 00:20:57,400
CO2 is over 3%. Two minutes
without a suite, you're dead.

181
00:20:59,400 --> 00:21:05,300
Peak, port side, 52.000. Makes
Everest look like a baby brother.

182
00:21:05,301 --> 00:21:07,800
Alright, take us round.

183
00:21:07,801 --> 00:21:11,000
We will use that as our point of entry.

184
00:21:11,600 --> 00:21:18,000
Terrain data rising up. We've got a
couple of hard spots. Could be metal.

185
00:21:37,800 --> 00:21:42,500
No radio, no heat source.
- Nobody's home.

186
00:21:42,501 --> 00:21:47,300
There's nothing in the
desert. No man needs nothing.

187
00:21:47,301 --> 00:21:52,100
What was that?
- Just something from a film I like.

188
00:21:56,200 --> 00:22:01,100
Let's go through that gateway.
Reduce air speed by 100 knots.

189
00:22:04,400 --> 00:22:08,200
Going through, nice and slow.

190
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:15,700
Keep her steady boys.
- There.

191
00:22:15,701 --> 00:22:17,800
What are you doing?

192
00:22:17,801 --> 00:22:20,700
Doctor Holloway why
don't you take a seat?!

193
00:22:21,800 --> 00:22:24,800
Right there. God does not
build in straight lines.

194
00:22:24,801 --> 00:22:28,900
Starboard side, this valley! Captain,
do you think you can put us down there?

195
00:22:28,901 --> 00:22:34,900
I wouldn't be any good if I couldn't do
that, Mr. Ravel, starboard 90 degrees.

196
00:22:39,500 --> 00:22:43,000
One mile, port bow.
- One mile, port bow.

197
00:22:43,001 --> 00:22:45,600
Engage landing sequence.
Switch to manual.

198
00:22:45,601 --> 00:22:50,500
Easy does it. Yeah baby, yeah.

199
00:22:52,000 --> 00:22:56,800
Putting her down in 5, 4...

200
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:01,900
2, easy does it.

201
00:23:35,400 --> 00:23:39,000
Captain, would you please tell
the survey team to suit up?

202
00:23:39,001 --> 00:23:42,400
And meet us in the air lock.
- There's only 6 hours left of daylight.

203
00:23:42,401 --> 00:23:46,500
Why don't you leave it 'till the morning?
- No, no, it's Christmas captain,

204
00:23:46,501 --> 00:23:48,800
and I want to open my presents.

205
00:23:48,801 --> 00:23:53,500
You, boy, you're coming with us.
- I'd be delighted.

206
00:24:03,400 --> 00:24:06,500
Hey Jackson, what's that for?

207
00:24:06,600 --> 00:24:12,000
Expedition security. My job is to
make sure everybody's nice and safe.

208
00:24:12,500 --> 00:24:16,000
This is a scientific
expedition, no weapons.

209
00:24:16,001 --> 00:24:19,500
Alright then. Good luck with that.

210
00:24:21,500 --> 00:24:24,900
David, why are wearing a suite?

211
00:24:24,901 --> 00:24:28,800
I beg your pardon?
- You don't breathe, remember?

212
00:24:28,801 --> 00:24:30,900
So, why wear a suit?

213
00:24:30,901 --> 00:24:34,500
I was designed like this
because you people are

214
00:24:34,501 --> 00:24:38,100
more comfortable interacting
with your own kind.

215
00:24:38,400 --> 00:24:42,800
If I didn't wear a suite,
it would defeat the purpose.

216
00:24:42,801 --> 00:24:47,700
Making you guys pretty close?
- Not to close I hope.

217
00:25:29,600 --> 00:25:33,000
This is just one small step for mankind.

218
00:25:33,001 --> 00:25:35,600
Seriously?

219
00:25:39,600 --> 00:25:43,200
Come on! You ready to
do this?! I know you are.

220
00:25:52,600 --> 00:25:54,999
Fifield, I want a
spectrograph on that structure,

221
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:57,400
I want to know if it's natural or
somebody put it there, alright?

222
00:25:57,401 --> 00:26:03,200
I can't tell you if it's natural or not,
but what I can tell you is, it's hollow.

223
00:26:26,500 --> 00:26:30,600
Prometheus, are you seeing this?

224
00:26:30,601 --> 00:26:33,900
Affirmative, we see you.

225
00:26:40,500 --> 00:26:44,000
Are you ready?
- Yeah. - Let's do it.

226
00:27:16,400 --> 00:27:19,500
After you.
- After you.

227
00:27:19,700 --> 00:27:23,700
Careful.
- Prometheus, we're going in.

228
00:27:23,701 --> 00:27:25,701
Copy that.

229
00:27:58,200 --> 00:28:02,500
Pause back here, some
kind of a corridor.

230
00:28:02,501 --> 00:28:07,600
Mr. Fifield, let's get a grid of the
structure, I want the whole interior.

231
00:28:07,601 --> 00:28:10,000
If there's anything in
here worth looking at,

232
00:28:10,001 --> 00:28:14,800
these pups will find them.
- Pups? - Yeah, my pups.

233
00:28:27,400 --> 00:28:30,800
Prometheus, we are now mapping.

234
00:28:34,100 --> 00:28:36,700
Copy that.

235
00:28:47,700 --> 00:28:50,800
I'll be damned.

236
00:29:03,100 --> 00:29:06,600
Fifield, you got a reading?
- Yeah.

237
00:29:06,601 --> 00:29:10,800
Pups are saying, this way.

238
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:30,800
Look at this.

239
00:29:36,800 --> 00:29:40,000
Oh Charlie...

240
00:29:42,500 --> 00:29:46,200
Jesus, sunlight's heating the water.

241
00:29:46,201 --> 00:29:50,100
Check out the humidity.
- Yeah, look at the CO2 levels.

242
00:29:50,101 --> 00:29:55,000
Outside it's completely toxic,
and in here there's nothing.

243
00:29:55,001 --> 00:29:57,600
It's breathable.

244
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:01,000
What are you doing?
Charlie, don't be an idiot.

245
00:30:01,001 --> 00:30:06,100
Don't be a sceptic. There's something
generating an atmosphere, David?

246
00:30:06,101 --> 00:30:09,300
Dr. Holloway is correct.
- Cleaner than ours, actually.

247
00:30:09,301 --> 00:30:12,300
They were terraforming here.
- Please, don't do...

248
00:30:12,301 --> 00:30:15,000
Ellie, I'm not wearing this thing anymore.

249
00:30:15,001 --> 00:30:19,600
<i>Wish me luck babe. - Do you copy,
do not remove your head gear.</i>

250
00:30:35,700 --> 00:30:39,100
You crazy bastard.

251
00:30:42,400 --> 00:30:45,749
Prometheus connect our suit cameras if you
want to continue watching this freak show,

252
00:30:45,750 --> 00:30:49,100
we are taking our helmets off.

253
00:30:49,101 --> 00:30:52,000
<i>Copy that, switching feeds.</i>

254
00:30:52,800 --> 00:30:55,800
Well come on, pay up.

255
00:30:55,801 --> 00:30:58,700
Pay what?
- What do you mean "pay what"?

256
00:30:58,701 --> 00:31:01,100
Something's manufacturing
breathable air down there.

257
00:31:01,101 --> 00:31:05,100
That means it's terraforming. - No, no,
the bet was why we came here.

258
00:31:05,101 --> 00:31:08,500
If you said that that old man wanted
to talk to Martians, then I'd pay

259
00:31:08,501 --> 00:31:11,000
Oh come on, a hundred
credits, put it towards

260
00:31:11,001 --> 00:31:13,500
a lap dance of miss
Vickers, how about that?

261
00:31:14,700 --> 00:31:17,300
It's minus 12 in here.

262
00:31:17,301 --> 00:31:21,600
So why is this water not frozen?

263
00:31:21,601 --> 00:31:24,300
Maybe it's Martian piss.

264
00:31:24,301 --> 00:31:30,500
That's your, scientific
theory? Is it, Mr. Biology?

265
00:31:34,400 --> 00:31:40,500
Well, whatever it is it sure is clean.

266
00:31:59,100 --> 00:32:01,300
Impressive.

267
00:32:19,800 --> 00:32:23,700
What was that?
- David?

268
00:32:23,701 --> 00:32:26,300
David?!

269
00:32:29,000 --> 00:32:31,600
David?!

270
00:32:38,600 --> 00:32:40,600
Ellie!

271
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:49,500
What the hell was that? - Aren't
you glad we didn't bring any weapons?

272
00:32:49,501 --> 00:32:53,200
Whose idea was that?!
- Keep up!

273
00:33:03,200 --> 00:33:06,000
Where did he go?

274
00:33:17,300 --> 00:33:20,500
There it is.

275
00:33:20,501 --> 00:33:25,200
Oh my God, Charlie we found them.
- What do you mean "them"?

276
00:33:25,900 --> 00:33:28,300
It is them Ellie.

277
00:33:28,301 --> 00:33:34,500
Looks like a door, and
he's been decapitated by it.

278
00:33:35,400 --> 00:33:38,700
Son of a bitch.

279
00:33:38,701 --> 00:33:41,600
They were right.

280
00:33:43,500 --> 00:33:46,600
Did you want them to be wrong?

281
00:33:49,300 --> 00:33:53,600
David, please tell me you can read that.

282
00:33:53,601 --> 00:33:56,100
Perhaps.

283
00:33:57,000 --> 00:34:00,600
I'm out of here.

284
00:34:00,601 --> 00:34:04,000
Fifield, where are you going?

285
00:34:04,001 --> 00:34:07,000
What?

286
00:34:07,001 --> 00:34:12,600
Look, I'm just a geologist,
I like rocks, I love rocks.

287
00:34:12,601 --> 00:34:15,400
It's clear you two don't
give a shit about rocks,

288
00:34:15,401 --> 00:34:18,900
but what you do seem to care
about is gigantic dead bodies

289
00:34:18,901 --> 00:34:24,800
I don't really have anything to
contribute in the gigantic dead body arena!

290
00:34:24,801 --> 00:34:29,900
I'm going to go back to the
ship, if you don't mind.

291
00:34:31,900 --> 00:34:36,300
Anyone want to join me? You staying?

292
00:34:36,800 --> 00:34:40,900
No, ship's good.
- Yeah, ship very good.

293
00:34:40,901 --> 00:34:47,100
Congratulations on meeting your maker.
- Thank you.

294
00:34:47,101 --> 00:34:50,900
Pull yourself together man.

295
00:34:52,100 --> 00:34:55,100
I thought you were the crazy one.

296
00:35:02,700 --> 00:35:05,900
Do you have the carbon reader?

297
00:35:06,500 --> 00:35:09,400
Thank you.

298
00:35:14,700 --> 00:35:17,800
How long has it been dead?

299
00:35:18,300 --> 00:35:22,300
Two thousand years, give or take.

300
00:35:24,400 --> 00:35:27,000
What are you doing David?

301
00:35:27,001 --> 00:35:29,800
I'm attempting to open the door.

302
00:35:29,801 --> 00:35:32,600
Wait, we don't know
what's on the other side.

303
00:35:33,400 --> 00:35:36,900
Ups, sorry.

304
00:35:39,300 --> 00:35:43,100
Look Ford, it's the head.

305
00:35:51,600 --> 00:35:54,900
An amazing state of preservation.

306
00:35:54,901 --> 00:35:58,600
We'll take it in.

307
00:36:00,800 --> 00:36:04,300
Remarkably human.

308
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:23,000
Beautiful painting.

309
00:36:23,001 --> 00:36:26,300
It's a mural.

310
00:36:36,800 --> 00:36:40,700
Stop, stop, don't touch it.
- Sorry.

311
00:36:41,100 --> 00:36:44,000
Please, don't touch anything.

312
00:36:44,001 --> 00:36:46,301
It's sweating.

313
00:37:23,500 --> 00:37:26,500
Organic.

314
00:37:31,300 --> 00:37:35,500
Oh no, Charlie the murals are changing.

315
00:37:35,501 --> 00:37:38,000
I think we've averted the
atmosphere in the room.

316
00:37:38,001 --> 00:37:40,900
<i>Charlie, do you copy?</i>

317
00:37:40,901 --> 00:37:45,900
Overhead, Ford quick,
help me bag the head.

318
00:37:55,600 --> 00:37:58,500
<i>Boss?
- What you got?</i>

319
00:37:58,501 --> 00:38:01,900
We got an incoming
storm front, silica and

320
00:38:01,901 --> 00:38:06,300
<i>lots of static, this is not good.
- I see it.</i>

321
00:38:08,700 --> 00:38:10,800
<i>Ground crew this is Janet.</i>

322
00:38:10,801 --> 00:38:13,300
<i>Need you to hustle back right now.</i>

323
00:38:13,301 --> 00:38:15,499
<i>Ground crew, do
you copy? I got 200 km</i>

324
00:38:15,500 --> 00:38:19,700
<i>winds of airborne silica and
enough static to fry your suit.</i>

325
00:38:19,701 --> 00:38:23,100
Copy that sir, but we
need more time here.

326
00:38:23,101 --> 00:38:26,000
I'll be closing the
outer doors in 15 minutes.

327
00:38:26,001 --> 00:38:29,100
<i>I sincerely hope you can make it.</i>

328
00:38:30,600 --> 00:38:35,600
Charlie, David, we must leave now!

329
00:38:36,500 --> 00:38:40,500
This is just another tomb.

330
00:38:42,800 --> 00:38:45,400
David?

331
00:38:48,700 --> 00:38:50,700
Let's go!

332
00:38:55,700 --> 00:38:59,100
David, we are leaving!

333
00:39:07,900 --> 00:39:10,900
Come on! Damn it,
they've already taken off.

334
00:39:10,901 --> 00:39:13,300
Come on, let's go.

335
00:39:13,301 --> 00:39:16,800
<i>Prometheus to ground crew,
you're running out of time.</i>

336
00:39:16,801 --> 00:39:19,300
Come on.

337
00:39:33,700 --> 00:39:36,400
Drive faster!

338
00:39:58,900 --> 00:40:01,300
Charlie, the head!

339
00:40:01,301 --> 00:40:04,200
Ellie stop! What are you doing?!

340
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:15,000
Shit

341
00:40:15,001 --> 00:40:17,300
Ellie hold on!

342
00:40:17,700 --> 00:40:20,300
<i>Goddamn it.
- Close it!</i>

343
00:41:26,400 --> 00:41:28,800
Got it.

344
00:41:33,400 --> 00:41:35,400
<i>Decontamination at level 3.</i>

345
00:41:35,401 --> 00:41:37,500
What was that Ellie?

346
00:41:37,501 --> 00:41:39,650
You could have compromised
the entire mission,

347
00:41:39,651 --> 00:41:41,800
not to mention almost killing yourself!

348
00:41:41,801 --> 00:41:46,500
Are you alright?
- Yes, thank you David.

349
00:41:46,501 --> 00:41:48,600
My pleasure.

350
00:41:48,601 --> 00:41:52,800
Alright doctors, it's real good to have
you back, but where is Millburn and Fifield?

351
00:41:52,801 --> 00:41:56,000
<i>Aren't they back yet?</i>

352
00:41:56,001 --> 00:41:58,500
Kick them up for me.

353
00:42:00,400 --> 00:42:05,900
We've been here before Fifield.
- I know, it all looks the same to me.

354
00:42:05,901 --> 00:42:08,600
<i>Boys this is the captain, listen up.</i>

355
00:42:08,601 --> 00:42:12,200
Between the static
electricity and the wind speed,

356
00:42:12,201 --> 00:42:15,100
there isn’t no safe way to come get you.

357
00:42:15,101 --> 00:42:19,500
<i>Temperature is dropping rapidly, so
get your helmets on and stay warm.</i>

358
00:42:19,501 --> 00:42:22,700
Till the storm passes.

359
00:42:22,701 --> 00:42:27,200
Captain, can you get a message to the
scientist and that zealot girlfriend of his?

360
00:42:27,201 --> 00:42:30,800
<i>Know what they’re paying me by?
- No. I think we got it.</i>

361
00:42:30,801 --> 00:42:34,100
<i>Tell them I said... themselves.</i>

362
00:42:34,101 --> 00:42:36,400
<i>Copy?
- Copy that.</i>

363
00:42:36,401 --> 00:42:41,100
Alright boys, keep your heads down
and we'll come get you in the morning.

364
00:42:58,900 --> 00:43:04,300
Sample is sterile, no contagion present.
- David.

365
00:43:06,100 --> 00:43:09,400
So are they all dead?

366
00:43:09,401 --> 00:43:13,900
What? Who?
- Your engineers.

367
00:43:13,901 --> 00:43:19,000
Are they all dead or aren't they?
- I don't know, we just got here.

368
00:43:19,001 --> 00:43:21,201
Scan.

369
00:43:22,200 --> 00:43:26,500
Do you even care if they're all dead?
- Weyland cared.

370
00:43:26,501 --> 00:43:30,300
Dr. Shaw, have a look at this.

371
00:43:33,300 --> 00:43:38,400
That's not an exoskeleton.
- No. - I think it's a helmet.

372
00:43:38,401 --> 00:43:43,000
Let's see if we can lift it up.
- Should be able to pry this open.

373
00:43:43,001 --> 00:43:47,100
It's too heavy for us, David.

374
00:43:52,400 --> 00:43:56,300
Careful.
- Like so.

375
00:44:09,700 --> 00:44:14,400
What is that on its head?
- It looks like neo cells.

376
00:44:14,401 --> 00:44:18,000
In a state of...
- Change. - Yes.

377
00:44:18,001 --> 00:44:20,001
Changing into what?

378
00:44:20,002 --> 00:44:22,500
Can you run a stim line
into Locus Coeruleus?

379
00:44:22,501 --> 00:44:26,600
I think we can trick the nervous
system into thinking it's still alive.

380
00:44:26,900 --> 00:44:30,900
30 amps.
- OK. - No more.

381
00:44:31,300 --> 00:44:35,500
Let me make an incision.
- OK.

382
00:44:40,500 --> 00:44:43,600
Go up, 40.

383
00:44:44,100 --> 00:44:46,500
OK, 40 up.

384
00:44:46,501 --> 00:44:49,400
Did you see that?

385
00:44:50,000 --> 00:44:53,500
See? Go up another 10.

386
00:44:53,501 --> 00:44:55,900
OK, up 10.

387
00:44:57,400 --> 00:45:01,500
Too much, go down 10.
- OK, down 10.

388
00:45:01,501 --> 00:45:05,500
Down another 20.
- I'm trying. - Ford, down.

389
00:45:06,700 --> 00:45:09,900
Ford, stop it!

390
00:45:09,901 --> 00:45:14,000
David, contain it now!
- Contain it, turn it off, now!

391
00:45:35,500 --> 00:45:38,100
Mortal after all.

392
00:45:44,500 --> 00:45:47,100
Ford take a sample.

393
00:45:47,101 --> 00:45:49,200
Let's have a look.

394
00:45:53,100 --> 00:45:56,100
No sir, I will take care of it.

395
00:45:56,101 --> 00:45:59,500
Yes sir I understand, I’m sorry.

396
00:45:59,501 --> 00:46:03,700
Unfortunately, slightly premature.

397
00:46:06,200 --> 00:46:09,100
Of course sir.

398
00:46:36,000 --> 00:46:39,000
Miss Vickers?

399
00:46:41,600 --> 00:46:46,400
What did he say David? - I don't
think he'd want me to tell you.

400
00:46:53,200 --> 00:46:58,200
What did he say?
- I'm sorry, that's confidential.

401
00:46:58,201 --> 00:47:04,900
So help me God, I will find the cord
that makes you run and I will cut it.

402
00:47:04,901 --> 00:47:08,200
What did he say?

403
00:47:08,700 --> 00:47:14,500
He said: "Try harder".

404
00:47:14,800 --> 00:47:19,700
Cup of tea, ma'am?

405
00:47:33,900 --> 00:47:39,500
Genetic view. - OK.
- Let's have a look at its DNA.

406
00:47:47,900 --> 00:47:50,800
Isolate the strand.

407
00:47:52,300 --> 00:47:56,200
Compare it to the gene sample.

408
00:47:56,201 --> 00:48:00,500
<i>Overlay.
- Processing.</i>

409
00:48:01,000 --> 00:48:03,600
<i>Processing.</i>

410
00:48:04,200 --> 00:48:07,500
<i>DNA match.</i>

411
00:48:07,800 --> 00:48:10,800
Oh my God...

412
00:48:29,500 --> 00:48:33,400
It's us, it's everything.

413
00:48:36,300 --> 00:48:39,000
What killed them?

414
00:48:55,900 --> 00:48:59,800
Big things have small beginnings.

415
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:12,500
Am I interrupting? Thought
you might be running low.

416
00:49:16,500 --> 00:49:21,300
Pour yourself a glass pal. - Thank you,
but I'm afraid it would be wasted on me.

417
00:49:21,301 --> 00:49:25,300
Right, I almost forgot
you're not a real boy.

418
00:49:27,200 --> 00:49:31,800
I'm very sorry that your engineers
are all gone, Dr. Holloway.

419
00:49:35,300 --> 00:49:39,100
You think we wasted our
time coming here, don't you?

420
00:49:39,101 --> 00:49:43,500
Your question depends on the understanding
what you hope to achieve by coming here.

421
00:49:43,501 --> 00:49:48,500
What we hoped to achieve, was to
meet our makers, to get answers.

422
00:49:48,501 --> 00:49:53,300
Why they even made
us in the first place.

423
00:49:54,500 --> 00:49:58,400
Why do you think your people made me?

424
00:49:58,401 --> 00:50:01,400
We made you cos we could.

425
00:50:02,300 --> 00:50:04,900
Can you imagine how
disappointing would be for you,

426
00:50:04,901 --> 00:50:08,500
to hear the same thing
from your creator?

427
00:50:12,500 --> 00:50:15,200
I guess it's a good thing
you can't be disappointed.

428
00:50:15,201 --> 00:50:21,000
Yes. It's wonderful actually.
May I ask you something?

429
00:50:21,500 --> 00:50:24,600
Please do.
- How far would you go,

430
00:50:24,601 --> 00:50:29,600
to get what you came all
this way for? Your answers?

431
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:34,600
What would you be willing to do?
- Anything and everything.

432
00:50:34,601 --> 00:50:36,901
That's worth drinking to, I'd imagine.

433
00:50:48,100 --> 00:50:51,500
Here's mud in your eye, pal.

434
00:50:54,300 --> 00:50:56,800
Good health.

435
00:51:00,600 --> 00:51:04,200
It's those things.

436
00:51:05,500 --> 00:51:08,500
Are they real?

437
00:51:08,501 --> 00:51:10,900
Of course they're real.

438
00:51:10,901 --> 00:51:17,500
Jesus Christ, look at the pile,
look how up they are.

439
00:51:18,500 --> 00:51:22,000
Looks like they were
running from something.

440
00:51:22,001 --> 00:51:24,200
Don't touch, OK?

441
00:51:24,201 --> 00:51:28,700
This thing is, opened
up from the inside,

442
00:51:28,701 --> 00:51:31,200
almost like its exploded.

443
00:51:31,201 --> 00:51:35,900
It's like a scene out of some
sort of holocaust painting.

444
00:51:55,300 --> 00:51:59,900
Whatever killed them
is long gone, right?

445
00:52:01,000 --> 00:52:05,300
Where is your position?
- Prometheus, this is Millburn.

446
00:52:05,301 --> 00:52:11,300
We are at 7401477, why?
- I just got a ping.

447
00:52:11,301 --> 00:52:15,700
About one click west of you.
- What do you mean, a ping?

448
00:52:16,700 --> 00:52:20,700
Whatever that probe is
picking up, it's not dead.

449
00:52:20,701 --> 00:52:23,600
It's reading life form.

450
00:52:23,601 --> 00:52:28,000
What do you mean a "life form"?
- Is it moving?

451
00:52:28,001 --> 00:52:31,600
No, I don't think so.

452
00:52:31,601 --> 00:52:34,500
Captain, you're obviously not
seeing what we're seeing down here,

453
00:52:34,501 --> 00:52:37,200
<i>but if you were, you wouldn't
be talking about bloody ping.</i>

454
00:52:37,201 --> 00:52:42,600
Boys, the signal's been coming
in sporadically since the storm hit.

455
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:46,500
<i>That's not good to us down here captain!</i>

456
00:52:47,000 --> 00:52:50,700
<i>Is it moving? Are these things moving?</i>

457
00:52:53,300 --> 00:52:56,800
No, it just disappeared actually.

458
00:52:56,801 --> 00:53:00,900
<i>Must be a glitch.
- What do you mean, "a glitch"?</i>

459
00:53:00,901 --> 00:53:04,800
Alright boys, sleep tight.

460
00:53:04,801 --> 00:53:09,200
<i>Try not to bother each other.
- Captain, what do you mean "a glitch"?</i>

461
00:53:09,201 --> 00:53:12,200
Millburn wait!

462
00:53:12,201 --> 00:53:17,700
<i>He said, one click west?</i>

463
00:53:19,700 --> 00:53:22,900
We don't want to go check
that out, do we? - Shit no.

464
00:53:22,901 --> 00:53:27,000
Where are we going to go?
- East.

465
00:53:27,001 --> 00:53:33,000
Yeah east. - Glitch man,
glitches life form, what the fuck?!

466
00:53:33,001 --> 00:53:37,300
Based on the behaviour of the subject
in these holographic recordings,

467
00:53:37,301 --> 00:53:40,800
we're still attempting to identify
what caused the head to combust.

468
00:53:40,801 --> 00:53:45,500
I can't help but wonder,
was there an outbreak here?

469
00:53:50,000 --> 00:53:54,600
You rang, ma'am?
- I have something important to tell you.

470
00:53:54,601 --> 00:53:58,800
What is that?
- This is a rose

471
00:53:58,801 --> 00:54:02,000
that I had frozen with the
champagne. I was going to give it to you

472
00:54:02,001 --> 00:54:04,800
when we found what we came for.

473
00:54:04,801 --> 00:54:08,500
We did find what we came for.
They were here, this is...

474
00:54:08,501 --> 00:54:14,600
The most significant discovery
in the history of mankind.

475
00:54:14,800 --> 00:54:17,700
I know.

476
00:54:18,100 --> 00:54:21,800
It's incredible, it really is, but...

477
00:54:21,801 --> 00:54:24,500
I wanted to talk to them.

478
00:54:24,501 --> 00:54:28,600
Don't you want to know why they came?

479
00:54:28,601 --> 00:54:32,300
Why they abandoned us?
I just want answers baby.

480
00:54:32,301 --> 00:54:37,600
We were right Charlie. I have proof.

481
00:54:38,400 --> 00:54:40,500
Look.

482
00:54:45,300 --> 00:54:48,600
Their genetic material predates ours.

483
00:54:48,601 --> 00:54:54,100
We come from them.
- Are you kidding me? - No.

484
00:54:56,200 --> 00:54:59,100
OK.

485
00:55:00,900 --> 00:55:04,600
I guess you can take your
father's cross off now.

486
